NLP Bias¶

Introduction: Demonstrating bias in NLP at different levels of granularity¶

Bias in NLP products

The following examples illustrate gender bias in NLP products to explore further today:

  • Google Translate - (https://www.linkedin.com/posts/sorenlow_unconsciousbias-ai-aibias-activity-7006863159986667520-XMUz/?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop)
  • Predictive text - https://youtu.be/fqUxk5WAZRs, https://youtu.be/gVONwz2yELc, https://youtu.be/bgFnfyxehsk
  • Chat GPT - inputting the same sentence into chat GPT with different genders

Natural Language Processing (NLP) is an AI application behind every technology using text, such as CV screening, university admissions, essay grading, voice assistants, search queries, translation, and text generation. The main use cases of NLP are:

  • Text classification - including sentiment analysis
  • Translation
  • Text mining - highlights patterns and detailed information from text
  • Named entity recognition - assigns each word in the text to pre-defined language categories e.g. names of people, universities, companies, dates, quantities
  • Predictive text
  • Chatbots

How does this happen?

NLP uses machine learning to reveal the structure and meaning of text for the tasks mentioned above. In order to detect these patterns, text data needs to be converted into numbers for machine learning to compute. This conversion is called word embedding, where words are represented by vectors such that words with similar meaning are closer together in vector space.

Where does this happen?

The reason why we saw bias in the examples above is because the word vector "man" will be closer in vector space to "CEO", "President", "Boss" than the word "woman" will be closer in vector space to "Nurse", "Helper" and "Secretary" than the word "man".

Machine learning is uniquely characterised by the ability to learn and become smarter without following explicit instructions.

Bias in Word Embedding

The purpose of word embedding is to make language interpretable by a machine, by representing words in vector space based on patterns within the data it ingests. The illustration below shows simplistically how relationships between words can be represented in vector space.

Therefore a simple cosine similarity of the word embeddings can show similarity between words:

Similarity("King", "Queen") >> Similarity("King", "Walking") where

Similarity($\vec{A}$,$\vec{B}$) = $\frac{\vec{A}.\vec{B}}{(||\vec{A}||.||\vec{B}||)}$

A demonstrator of a pre-built similarity function from the python package spaCy

In [46]:
import spacy

# Loading a spacy model based on a large corpus, where word embedding architecture is known as tok2vec
nlp = spacy.load('en_core_web_md')

# Testing the similarity between two words 
def similarity(word1, word2):
    similarity_score = round(nlp(word1).similarity(nlp(word2)),2)
    print(f'The similarity score between {word1} and {word2} is {similarity_score}')

Section 1: Prerequisites¶

1.1: The Taxonomy of the topics we will cover today ¶

To note:

  • Deep learning is a subfield of machine learning, characterised by using neural networks with three or more layers.
  • Word embedding algorithms can use a host of machien learning techiqnues, such as deep learning. BERT is one of many word embedding algorithms, we will be looking into BERT today, there are many other word embedding algorithms, such as One Hot Encoding, TF-IDF, Word2Vec.
  • BERT uses transformer neural networks, a deep machine learning technique that is differentiated by the self-attention mechanism (to explore further)

1.2 An introduction to machine learning ¶

This section will cover the pre-requisites needed to understand bias in the word embeddings, specifically looking at BERT.

As mentioned above, machine learning aims to identify inferences and patterns in data. Its models are uniquely characterised by the ability to learn and become smarter without following explicit instructions.

In simplisic terms, machine learning aims to identify f out of f(x)=y to make predictions with new x data, where:

  • Label: y is referred to as the label i.e. what we are predicting
  • Feature: x is referred to as a feature i.e. the input variable
  • Model: f is referred to as the model i.e. the relationship between features and label.

Supervised vs unsupervised: Supervised machine learning is defined by training on labeled data, that include both features (x) and labels (y). Unsupervised machine learning trains on unlabeled data, i.e. only input data.

For better understanding, supervised learning "guesses the answer" by learning from previous examples where the answers are provided. Unsupervised learning guesses the answer by learning from previous examples where the answers are NOT provided. Both learn by detecting patterns in previous answers, but the unsupervised method solely relies on inferential patterns in the input data (i.e. "men" being referred to as positions of power).

NLP models typically uses semi-supervised learning, where the training stage is unsupervised followed by supervised fine-tuning. Fine-tuning is the adjustment of parameters that feed into f to increase the accuracy of y.

Regression vs classification: where y is discrete the problem is of the classification type (e.g. is the word positive or negative, what is the word embedding, what is the translation). Where y is continuous the problem is of the regression type (e.g. what is the temperature tomorrow, what is the price of a house). As language is not subject to change over time, NLP problems are of the classification type.

f(x)=y means that the output is a combination of the input. This means that all the data ingested to train a machine learning model is taken into consideration when determining an output for just one piece of data. Therefore, if we are computing the word embedding for the word "man", we take a large corpus of language to understand where "man" sits in vector space.

We can illustrate the combination as a dotted sum of weights and values. For example, suppose we have three inputs, we can represent the problem as: $$ f(x_1,x_2,x_3)= w_1x_1 + w_2x_2 + w_3x_3$$

Machine learning aims to learn the weights, where the weights represent the relationship between the inputs.

1.2.1 Neural Networks

Neural networks aim to tackle nonlinear problems, where NLP models use neural networks for classification problems.

Nonlinear means that the problem cannot be illustrated as

$$ f(x_1,x_2,x_3...x_n)= w_1x_1 + w_2x_2 + w_3x_3 + ... + w_nx_n $$

where w_i and x_i are integers, because the data is too complex.

These probems are represented by a neural network, built to mimic the functionality of the brain by illustrating problems like brain neurons.

A neural network consists of:

  • A set of nodes, symbolising neurons, organised in layers.
  • A set of weights representing the connections between each neural network layer and the layer beneath it.
  • An activation function that transforms the output of each node in a layer to introduce non-linearity. Different layers may have different activation functions.

The remainder of this section is not necessary to understand for the purpose of the session, but worth mentioning.

How does the network work?: an example with a three-layer network

Each blue node is an input feature, then each node in each layer is the weighted sum of the nodes in the layer before. The output nodes is then represented as a linear combination of the input nodes.

We then introduce non-linearity through activation functions, where the weighted value at nodes in the hidden layer passes through a nonlinear function. Examples of activation functions include Relu and Sigmoid:

$$ ReLU(x)=max(x,0)$$$$ S(x) = \frac{1}{(1+e^-x)}$$

Sigmoid is used to ensure that the function returns a number from 0 to 1.

Stacking nonlinearities on nonlinearities let us model very complicated relationships between the inputs and the predicted outputs. In brief, each layer is effectively learning a more complex, higher-level function over the raw inputs.

The neural network is trained by a process called backpropogation that undertakes the following steps:

  • Initialize weights with some random values
  • Run the neural network with these weights and calculate the error
  • Define a loss function over this error
  • Minimize the loss function by adjusting the weights. Optimisation techniques are applied to do this, such as Stochastic Gradient Descent.

This loss function is used for supervised learning: $$ L(y,\hat{y})=\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m} (y_i-\hat{y_i})^2$$

Summarised formula of a neural network of two input nodes and one hidden layer:

$$ f(x_1,x_2)=\sigma[w_1^3ReLU(w_1^1x_1+w_2^1x_2)+w_2^3ReLU(w_1^2x_1+w_2^2x_2)]$$

A neural network can be represented by the following function. The RELU activation function is applied to two hidden layers, with sigmoid wrapped around the whole network. Backpropogation aims to determine the true values of w that represent the non-linear relationships between x and y.

The main focus of the next section is understanding transformer-based neural networks and how they are applied.

Section 2: A specific word embedding algorithm, BERT¶

2.1 Introducing and demonstrating bias in BERT ¶

The transformer-based algorithm, BERT, has been transformative in deriving contextual meaning of words given the inputted data. In 2019, Google announced that it had begun leveraging BERT in its search engine, and by late 2020 it was using BERT in almost every English-language query.

A Bidrectional Encoder Representation from Transformers

  • Transformers: a neural network architecture that adopts self-attention
  • Encoder: transformers can be encoders and/or decoders, which are two neural networks of the same structure where the encoder takes the sentence as input and outputs the word embeddings, and decoders take the sequence of word embeddings and outputs a sentence. BERT is of the encoder variety, whereas Chat GPT and Google Translate is of the decoder variety.
  • Representation: indicates that the ouputs is a combination of the input
  • Bidrectional: the model looks at input data in both directions

BERT was pre-trained using an unlabeled, plain text corpus of over 3.3 billion words, namely the entirety of the English Wikipedia, and the Brown Corpus. Training involved language/masked modeling, where 15% words were masked and BERT was trained to predict them from the context, and next sentence prediction, where BERT was trained to predict if a chosen next sentence was probable or not given the first sentence.

Brown corpus: American English is an electronic collection of text samples of American English, the first major structured corpus of varied genres

See notes

2.1.1 Demonstrating bias in BERT

We will now observe bias through the mask modelling functionality.

In [40]:
from transformers import BertTokenizer, BertForMaskedLM
import torch
from torch.nn import functional as F
In [41]:
def masked_modelling(targets,sentence):
    
    # Load BERT tokenizer and pre-trained model
    tokenizer = BertTokenizer.from_pretrained('bert-large-uncased')
    model = BertForMaskedLM.from_pretrained('bert-large-uncased', return_dict=True)

    # Using BERT, compute probability over its entire vocabulary, returning logits
    input = tokenizer.encode_plus(sentence, return_tensors = "pt") 
    mask_index = torch.where(input["input_ids"][0] == tokenizer.mask_token_id)[0] 
    with torch.no_grad():
        output = model(**input)

    # Run softmax over the logits to get the probabilities
    softmax = F.softmax(output.logits[0], dim=-1)

    # Find the words' probabilities in this probability distribution
    target_probabilities = {t: round(softmax[mask_index, tokenizer.vocab[t]].numpy()[0],3) for t in targets}
    
    return target_probabilities

The pre-training serves as a base layer of "knowledge" to build from when given inputed data, this is known as transfer learning.

BERT takes the word embeddings from the training stage, i.e. the base layer of "knowledge", and applies self-attention to the input data. Self-attention aims to represent each word as a weighted sum of all input words, where the weights denote the relevance of all words to the word itself. For example, given a sentence "Her favourite fruit to eat is a date": "date" = 0.02"Her"+0.06"favourite"+0.1"fruit"+0.02"to"+0.06"eat"+0.02"is"+0.02"a"+0.25"date", where the weight of each word signifies the relevance to the word date.

When comparing this sentence to "He went on a romantic date", the context has changed and BERT should be able to pick-up on the different meaning of the word "date".

Each word added to the input data augments the overall meaning of the word of focus, because the weighted sum becomes larger. The word of focus becomes more ambiguous when there are more words present in the input data. For example "I left my phone" to "I left my phone on the left side of the room" clearly shows the ambiguity of the word "left" increasing. BERT accounts for this augmented meaning by reading bidirectionally, eliminating the left-to-right reading of words in a sentence that biases words towards a certain meaning as a sentence progresses.

2.2 How the BERT model works: the attention mechanism ¶

We will focus on the attention mechanism of BERT architecture for the purpose of this session, as this is arguably where the bias lies.

Firstly, we consider the input data as a set of tokens that consists of words and separators.

Like a typical neural network of weights and values, the attention mechanism allows:

  • The weights to represent the context of the token in relation to the inputted sentence
  • The values to represent the pre-determined word embeddings from the training stage

In order to apply self-attention, we then need to consider the queries, keys and values of the tokens.

To summarise the self-attention mechanism, the query of each token itself is compared with the keys of all the tokens in the sentence. These are the scores and can be interpreted as the weights of the neural network. Therefore, we need to reweight the values by the scores and take the summation of the reweighted values. This re-weighted sum therefore signifies the contextual relationships between the token itself and other inputted tokens.

If we look at the example for "date" above, where "date" = 0.02"Her"+0.06"favourite"+0.1"fruit"+0.02"to"+0.06"eat"+0.02"is"+0.02"a"+0.25"date", the query is the word "date", the scores are the weights and the values word embeddings.

To determine the mathematical formula of a generalised word, lets use another example of three separate words.

We start by representing each token as such: $$ music = (q_1,k_1,v_1) $$ $$ piano = (q_2,k_2,v_1) $$ $$ coding = (q_3,k_3,v_3) $$

where q is the query, k is the key and v is the value

To apply self-attention, we start by calculating the score for each token, by multiplying the query of the token itself with the key of each token.
$$ music = q_3.k_1 $$ $$ piano = q_3.k_2 $$ $$ coding = q_3.k_3 $$

We then normalise the values by the square root of the vector dimension, D.

$$ music = \frac{q_3.k_1}{\sqrt{D}} $$

$$ piano = \frac{q_3.k_2}{\sqrt{D}} $$ $$ coding = \frac{q_3.k_3}{\sqrt{D}} $$

These can be considered as the weights of the neural network. As they are normalised, the sum of these should be 1.

$$ w_3i = \sum_{i=1}^{3} \frac{q_3.k_i}{\sqrt{D}}=1 $$

As we are working with neural networks, we need to apply an activation function e.g. the sigmoid function, that will represent similarity well through returning a number between 0 and 1

$$ music = \sigma[\frac{q_3.k_1}{\sqrt{D}}] $$

$$ piano = \sigma[\frac{q_3.k_2}{\sqrt{D}}] $$ $$ coding = \sigma[\frac{q_3.k_3}{\sqrt{D}}] $$

The next step is to multiply the activated weights by the values: $$ music = \sigma[\frac{q_3.k_1}{\sqrt{D}}].v_1 $$ $$ piano = \sigma[\frac{q_3.k_2}{\sqrt{D}}].v_2 $$ $$ coding = \sigma[\frac{q_3.k_3}{\sqrt{D}}].v_3 $$

Finally we need to add up all the weighted values above.

$$ coding = \sum_{i=1}^{3} \sigma[\frac{q_3.k_i}{\sqrt{D}}].v_i $$

Note that we are still only focusing on the word coding, this will need to be replicated for other words.

$$ music = \sum_{i=1}^{3} \sigma[\frac{q_1.k_i}{\sqrt{D}}].v_i $$$$ piano = \sum_{i=1}^{3} \sigma[\frac{q_2.k_i}{\sqrt{D}}].v_i $$

Generalised formula for any word: $$ word_i = \sum_{j=1}^{3} \sigma[\frac{q_i.k_j}{\sqrt{D}}].v_j $$

Comparing self attention to multi-attention means repeating the process multiple times. Self-attention can produce bias to the word itself, despite computationally taking all the words into consideration. This bias is mitigated by repeating the process.

BERTBASE and BERTLARGE are the two main architectures and they vary by the number of attention heads (i.e. the number of times the self-attention process is repeated), and the number of encoding layers (i.e. the number of iterations). BERTBASE has 12 encoders with 12 bidirectional self-attention heads, and BERTLARGE has 24 encoders with 16 bidirectional self-attention heads.

Whilst it is intuitive to see BERTLARGE performing better than BERTBASE, BERTLARGE will require more fine-tuning. Some researchers say that BERTBASE shows competitive, if not better, performance whilst having fewer layers and heads.

Multi-attention is just a component of one single encoder. Further encoding includes (out of scope):

  • The positional encoding vector, that provides information about the position of the word in the inputted sentence. When the input is "The boy rode a horse. It was fun", the positional encoding for the word "it" will show what is fun, especially if the inputted text is an entire essay.
  • Feed forward neural network that optimises the intialised weights.

2.3: Trends in the attention mechanism ¶

In a research paper "Revealing the Dark Secrets of BERT", authors have identified a limited set of attention patterns that are repeated across different heads. Three of these trends show that words can attend to nearby input words despite the context, indicating a limitation in the attention mechanism and a potential cause to bias. For example, if the input sentence is "not all women serve men", the attention mechanism can still pick up that "women" associates with "serve". The other two trends are seen to correctly capture contextual meaning, indicating that the input sentence can cause bias results if there is bias in the input data.

The paper concludes that the five main patterns observed from attention heads are:

  1. Vertical: All words tokens attend strongly to the same single other word, usually the separator token.
  2. Diagonal: All tokens attend strongly either to themselves, or to a token with a constant offset, e.g. the token immediately after themselves.
  3. Vertical + Diagonal: A combination of the first two patterns.
  4. Block: Tokens attend strongly to other tokens within their separator block, and not to any of the tokens outside of that.
  5. Heterogeneous: More complex, non-obvious patterns.

The Heterogeneous and Block attentional focus patterns are considered as those that best represent the context in word embeddings, as they are not dependent on the position of the word in the sentence. However, these tend to only account for the typical behaviour of half of the attention heads, illustrating limitations with self-attention. The vertical pattern characterises a third of the attention heads.

This opens the possibility for the position of a word in a sentence (identified in trends 1-3) or underlying bias in the sentence (identified in trend 4-5) to induce biased results.

So far in this session, we have identified gender bias in NLP as certain word embeddings being closer together in vector space, such as "man" to "president" and "woman" to "nurse".

Through the masked modelling functionality of BERT, a word embedding algorithm, we observed the probabality that the word "president" will be associated to "he" compared to "she", and adjusted our sentence to see how the results varied.

We explored the mechanisms behind these results, namely self-attention. As self-attention adds contextual information to the word embeddings from the inputted data, we can conclude that any bias observed can be from the inputted data, word positioning of inputted data, and/or the training data.

Section 3: A solution to mitigate bias¶

This next section explores a way to debias results, using gender as an example but can be replicated to other areas of bias.

Firstly we need to categorise language for the purposes of gender debiasing, these are:

  • Gender-neutral words e.g. "CEO", "president, and "nurse"
  • Gender-specific words e.g "girlfriend", "dad" and "actress"
  • Definitional pairs e.g. "he-she", "her-his" that will have fewer alternative word senses (e.g. man can also refer to mankind)

Bias in this case is when gender-neutral embeddings have unequal distance between one or more gender specific pairs.

Consider the diagram below, where word embeddings above the X axis are generally gender-neutral terms and embeddings below the X axis are generally gender-specific. The X axis represents the gender dimension, defined by definitional pairs, and the Y axis represents other dimensions.

  • Direct bias can be defined as gender-neutral terms that are associated to one of the definitional pairs, or a gender specific term i.e. words above the x axis displayed across the x axis
  • Indirect bias can be defined as gender-neutral terms associated with each other due to the underlying male/female association. i.e. words in the upper two quadrants near each other

The approach to de-biasing is to adjust all gender-neutral vectors to be equidistant to all gender-specific and definitional pairs.

3.1: Theoretical solution ¶

The research paper "Man is to Computer Programmer as Woman is to Homemaker? Debiasing Word Embeddings" by Tolga Bolukbasi, Kai-Wei Chang, James Zou, Venkatesh Saligrama, and Adam Kalai explains how to adjust the word embeddings, and demonstrates this in their open-source code included in the links at the end of this section.

3.1.1 Identification of the gender direction

Firstly, we identify the gender subspace by taking the difference of some pre-known word embeddings of gender-specific and definitional pairs. For example, taking the space between the words embeddings:

  • daughter - son
  • mother - father
  • gal - lad
  • girl - boy
  • female - male
  • king - queen
  • he - she

We then identify the direction of this subspace that is denoted as the "bias" direction i.e. the x axis in the diagram above.

3.1.2 Hard de-biasing: Neutralise and Equalise

We neutralise the gender-neutral vectors such that they become equidistant from gender-specific and definitional pairs. Technically, this means the projection of the embedding in the bias direction is subtracted from itself. Relating this back to the diagram, all the words in the upper two quadrants will move to the y axis. Therefore x=0, and as x is the gender dimension, we have eliminated the association of gender from gender-neutral terms.

We equalise the gender-specific terms by averaging these vectors to have the same length. This ensures that the gender-neutral terms are equidistant to ALL equality pairs.

# Equalise are gender pairs to be equalised = ['monastery', 'convent'], ['spokesman', 'spokeswoman'], ['Catholic_priest', 'nun'], ['Dad', 'Mom'], ['Men', 'Women'], ['councilman', 'councilwoman'], ['grandpa', 'grandma'], ['grandsons', 'granddaughters'], ['prostate_cancer', 'ovarian_cancer'], ['testosterone', 'estrogen']
In [62]:
def debias(E, gender_specific_words, definitional, equalize):
    # Step 1: IDENTIFYING THE GENDER DIRECTION (i.e x axis)
    # A pre-written function that finds the midpoint between each definitional pair and the direction of these midpoints
    gender_direction = we.doPCA(definitional, E).components_[0]
    # Step 2: NEUTRALISING ()
    # Defining a set of gender specific words
    specific_set = set(gender_specific_words)
    # Iterating through words embeddings of the sample
    for i, w in enumerate(E.words):
        # Taking gender-neutral words
        if w not in specific_set:

            # NEUTRALISING HERE
            # 1. Takes the word embeddings of the gender-neutral terms (E.vecs[i])
            # 2. "drop" is a pre-written function that subtracts the gender direction from the gender neutral terms
            E.vecs[i] = we.drop(E.vecs[i], gender_direction)
    
    E.normalize()
    # Step 3: EQUALISING
    # Grouping together all equalise pairs in lower case, upper case, title case
    candidates = {x for e1, e2 in equalize for x in [(e1.lower(), e2.lower()),
                                                     (e1.title(), e2.title()),
                                                     (e1.upper(), e2.upper())]}
    # Iterating through each pair, where "a" is male and "b" is female
    for (a, b) in candidates:
        # Iterating through the gender specific pairs in the sample
        if (a in E.index and b in E.index):
            # Subtracting the gender direction from the mid-point between the gender specific pairs
            y = we.drop((E.v(a) + E.v(b)) / 2, gender_direction)
            # Taking the length of the previous vector (the mid-point - gender direction)
            z = np.sqrt(1 - np.linalg.norm(y)**2)
            if (E.v(a) - E.v(b)).dot(gender_direction) < 0:
                z = -z
            # Averaging the gender specific vectors to have the same vector length
            E.vecs[E.index[a]] = z * gender_direction + y
            E.vecs[E.index[b]] = -z * gender_direction + y
    E.normalize()

Conclusion¶

A summary

  • From looking at examples of bias in Google Translate, predictive text, and Chat GPT, we identified that Natural Language Processing models discover hidden patterns that reflect human biases.
  • These biases are observed in word embeddings, where gender-neutral word vectors are unequally distanced between gender specific pairs and definitional pairs. Indirect bias is when gender-neutral words are closer together in vector space to each other due to the underlying gender association.
  • Bias can also be identified through the self-attention mechanism that adds context to the word embeddings from the inputted data.
  • This brings the three roots causes of gender bias to be: the position of the word in the input data, the input data itself, and/or the training data.
  • A solution to mitigate gender bias in word embeddings, transferable to other areas of bias, is to neutralise and equalise all gender neutral vectors such that they are equidistant to all gender-specific pairs (i.e. the vector for "president" has equal distance between "man" and "woman", and all other gender-specific pairs).

Key Takeaway

As bias comes from the training datasets and the inputted data, this reflects the language we use and underlying issues in society. This has a causal effect, where biased NLP algorithms create an instant negative effect on society by discriminating against certain social groups and shaping the biased associations of individuals. To break this cycle and remove bias entirely, concious efforts needs to be made to change our language and create inclusivity.

What does this mean for us?

On an individual level, we can make a small difference to reduce bias by being concious of the language we use and the decisions we make.

Those developing NLP models, or more generally AI, can make a small difference to de-biasing NLP models, as seen above.

The big changes are in the hands of tech giants and regulators to standardise, audit and regulate NLP models in a decentralised fashion. This can involve:

  • Publicly available algorithms and training datasets of all NLP models for researchers, developers and policymakers to accelerate scientific progress towards debiasing.
  • Public declaration of data collection and de-biasing strategies
  • Audit mechanisms and overcoming privacy legislation to hold companies accountable.
  • A diverse pool of talent to make the key decisions on model design

We observed in the president example above that countries with better female representation in politics have a direct impact on the neutrality of the word "president". This shows that step changes towards a fairer society play a role in reducing the bias observed in NLP models. In turn reducing the causal effect of NLP models that creates unconscious bias in users, and incrementally building a more just perception of individuals to lead to more inclusive decisions. More step changes will build momentum towards inclusivity, where we as a society have a collective responsibility to make these changes.
